{"title_page": "Cyril Stein", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Cyril Stein\n| image        =\n| image_size   =\n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1928|2|20|mf=y}}\n| birth_place  = London, England\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|2011|2|15|1928|2|20|mf=y}}\n| death_place  = Jerusalem\n| death_cause  = \n| restingplace = \n| nationality  = \n| religion     = \n| ethnicity    = \n| residence    = \n| education    = West Ham Grammar School\n| alma mater   = \n| occupation   = Businessman\n| title        = Chairman, [[Ladbrokes]] (1966-1993)\n| term         = \n| predecessor  = \n| successor    = \n| known for    = \n| boards       = \n| salary       = \n| networth     = \n| spouse       = Betty Young\n| parents      = \n| children     = Jonathan, Daniel and Marion Stein\n| relations    = \n| website      =\n}}\n\n'''Cyril Stein''' (20 February 1928 - 15 February 2011) was an English [[bookmaker]], businessman and finally [[Philanthropy|philanthropic]] supporter of many Jewish causes and charities who first bought [[Ladbrokes]] in 1956, then floated it in 1967 and finally left it in 1993.<ref name=\"times obit\">''[[The Times]]'' (London), obituary Thursday February 17, 2011</ref><ref name=\"thejc\">[http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/45297/ladbrokes-founder-cyril-stein-dies The Jewish Chronicle], February 17, 2011</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in the [[East End of London]] into a family of immigrants from Russia. His father, known as \u201cHonest Jack\u201d, worked for the [[London and Provincial Sporting News Agency]], which relayed information between off-course bookmakers and racecourses. Cyril Stein was educated at [[West Ham Grammar School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/finance-obituaries/8343803/Cyril-Stein.html|title=Cyril Stein|author=|date=23 February 2011|publisher=|accessdate=10 April 2018|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> Stein did his best to shun publicity and said one of his main concerns was to keep his family out of the limelight. He married Betty Young in 1949. He was survived by his wife sons Jonathan and Daniel and daughter Marion,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/obituary-cyril-stein-bookmaker-and-businessman-1-1501687|title=Obituary: Cyril Stein, bookmaker and businessman|author=|date=|website=scotsman.com|accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref> and several grandchildren.\n\nAn Orthodox Jew, he was never seen at a racetrack on a Saturday, the Jewish Sabbath, and was frequently seen in public wearing a knitted [[kippah]].{{cn|date=April 2020}} He used his money and influence to try to keep the [[West Bank]], including [[East Jerusalem]], in Israeli hands, and built a large estate in the centre of Jerusalem.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nAs a [[Zionism|committed Zionist]] throughout his life, Stein spent much of his latter years in Israel.{{cn|date=April 2020}} Stein was a major funder of the [[Labour Friends of Israel]] along with [[Trevor Chinn]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newleftproject.org/index.php/site/article_comments/the_uks_pro_israel_lobby_in_context|title=The UK\u2019s Pro-Israel Lobby in Context|publisher=New Left Project|date=27 November 2013}}</ref>{{Dead link}\n\n==Business career==\nStein ran his own small credit-betting office in the [[West End of London]] when (aged 28) he teamed up in 1956 with his bookmaker uncle Mark, who traded as Max Parker, to buy the venerable but failing bookmarking firm of [[Ladbrokes]], founded in 1886, for a reported \u00a3100,000.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nAppointed chairman of [[Ladbrokes]] in 1966 and some 12 months before the company was successfully floated on the [[London Stock Exchange]] with an initial market capitalization of \u00a31-million. Cyril Stein remained chairman until stepping down at the end of 1993 (aged 65) by which time the company was valued in excess of \u00a32-billion.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Philanthropy==\nHe was:<ref name=\"times obit\"/>\n* Vice-president of United Joint Israel Appeal (UJIA)\n* Supporter of the [[Jewish National Fund]] (JNF), including\n** Chair of the JNF Negev redevelopment project\n* Trustee of the Jewish Education Development Trust\n* Trustee and chairman of the Governors of [[Carmel College (Oxfordshire)|Carmel College]], Wallingford, Oxfordshire (UK)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/finance-obituaries/8343803/Cyril-Stein.html# Obituary in The Telegraph]\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/business/2011/mar/06/cyril-stein-obituary Obituary in The Guardian]\n* [https://archive.is/20130201211937/http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/obituaries/Obituary-Cyril-Stein-bookmaker-and.6720077.jp Obituary in The Scotsman]\n* [http://www.ladbrokesplc.com/about-ladbrokes/history.aspx The Ladbrokes Story]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stein, Cyril}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:Bookmakers]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:English Orthodox Jews]]\n[[Category:Labour Friends of Israel]]\n[[Category:People in greyhound racing]]\n[[Category:British Zionists]]\n[[Category:English people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to Israel]]\n[[Category:English philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Jewish British philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from London]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) donors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Cyril Stein\n| image        =\n| image_size   =\n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1928|2|20|mf=y}}\n| birth_place  = London, England\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|2011|2|15|1928|2|20|mf=y}}\n| death_place  = Jerusalem\n| death_cause  = \n| restingplace = \n| nationality  = \n| religion     = \n| ethnicity    = \n| residence    = \n| education    = West Ham Grammar School\n| alma mater   = \n| occupation   = Businessman\n| title        = Chairman, [[Ladbrokes]] (1966-1993)\n| term         = \n| predecessor  = \n| successor    = \n| known for    = \n| boards       = \n| salary       = \n| networth     = \n| spouse       = Betty Young\n| parents      = \n| children     = Jonathan, Daniel and Marion Stein\n| relations    = \n| website      =\n}}\n\n'''Cyril Stein''' (20 February 1928 - 15 February 2011) was an English [[bookmaker]], businessman and finally [[Philanthropy|philanthropic]] supporter of many Jewish causes and charities who first bought [[Ladbrokes]] in 1956, then floated it in 1967 and finally left it in 1993.<ref name=\"times obit\">''[[The Times]]'' (London), obituary Thursday February 17, 2011</ref><ref name=\"thejc\">[http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/45297/ladbrokes-founder-cyril-stein-dies The Jewish Chronicle], February 17, 2011</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in the [[East End of London]] into a family of immigrants from Russia. His father, known as \u201cHonest Jack\u201d, worked for the [[London and Provincial Sporting News Agency]], which relayed information between off-course bookmakers and racecourses. Cyril Stein was educated at [[West Ham Grammar School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/finance-obituaries/8343803/Cyril-Stein.html|title=Cyril Stein|author=|date=23 February 2011|publisher=|accessdate=10 April 2018|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> Stein did his best to shun publicity and said one of his main concerns was to keep his family out of the limelight. He married Betty Young in 1949. He was survived by his wife sons Jonathan and Daniel and daughter Marion,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/obituary-cyril-stein-bookmaker-and-businessman-1-1501687|title=Obituary: Cyril Stein, bookmaker and businessman|author=|date=|website=scotsman.com|accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref> and several grandchildren.\n\nAn Orthodox Jew, he was never seen at a racetrack on a Saturday, the Jewish Sabbath, and was frequently seen in public wearing a knitted [[kippah]].{{cn|date=April 2020}} He used his money and influence to try to keep the [[West Bank]], including [[East Jerusalem]], in Israeli hands, and built a large estate in the centre of Jerusalem.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nAs a [[Zionism|committed Zionist]] throughout his life, Stein spent much of his latter years in Israel.{{cn|date=April 2020}} Stein was a major funder of the [[Labour Friends of Israel]] along with [[Trevor Chinn]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newleftproject.org/index.php/site/article_comments/the_uks_pro_israel_lobby_in_context|title=The UK\u2019s Pro-Israel Lobby in Context|publisher=New Left Project|date=27 November 2013}}</ref>{{Dead link}\n\n==Business career==\nStein ran his own small credit-betting office in the [[West End of London]] when (aged 28) he teamed up in 1956 with his bookmaker uncle Mark, who traded as Max Parker, to buy the venerable but failing bookmarking firm of [[Ladbrokes]], founded in 1886, for a reported \u00a3100,000.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nAppointed chairman of [[Ladbrokes]] in 1966 and some 12 months before the company was successfully floated on the [[London Stock Exchange]] with an initial market capitalization of \u00a31-million. Cyril Stein remained chairman until stepping down at the end of 1993 (aged 65) by which time the company was valued in excess of \u00a32-billion.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Philanthropy==\nHe was:<ref name=\"times obit\"/>\n* Vice-president of United Joint Israel Appeal (UJIA)\n* Supporter of the [[Jewish National Fund]] (JNF), including\n** Chair of the JNF Negev redevelopment project\n* Trustee of the Jewish Education Development Trust\n* Trustee and chairman of the Governors of [[Carmel College (Oxfordshire)|Carmel College]], Wallingford, Oxfordshire (UK)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/finance-obituaries/8343803/Cyril-Stein.html# Obituary in The Telegraph]\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/business/2011/mar/06/cyril-stein-obituary Obituary in The Guardian]\n* [https://archive.is/20130201211937/http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/obituaries/Obituary-Cyril-Stein-bookmaker-and.6720077.jp Obituary in The Scotsman]\n* [http://www.ladbrokesplc.com/about-ladbrokes/history.aspx The Ladbrokes Story]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stein, Cyril}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:Bookmakers]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:English Orthodox Jews]]\n[[Category:Labour Friends of Israel]]\n[[Category:People in greyhound racing]]\n[[Category:British Zionists]]\n[[Category:English people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to Israel]]\n[[Category:English philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Jewish British philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from London]]\n", "name_user": "HonkyDory64", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyril_Stein"}
